### While Loop in C#

The `while` loop executes a block of code as long as a specified condition is true.

### Syntax

```csharp
while (condition)
{
    // Code to repeat
}
```

### Basic Example

```csharp
int i = 0;
while (i < 5)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Count: {i}");
    i++;
}
```

### Loop Flow

1. Check condition
2. If true, execute block
3. Go back to step 1
4. If false, exit loop

### Infinite Loop

```csharp
while (true)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Press Q to quit");
    var key = Console.ReadKey();
    if (key.Key == ConsoleKey.Q)
        break;
}
```

### Common Use Cases

| Use Case | Example |
|----------|---------|
| Reading data until end | `while ((line = reader.ReadLine()) != null)` |
| User input validation | `while (!int.TryParse(input, out num))` |
| Game loop | `while (isRunning) { Update(); Render(); }` |
| Retry logic | `while (attempts < maxRetries)` |

### Input Validation Pattern

```csharp
int age;
Console.Write("Enter age: ");
while (!int.TryParse(Console.ReadLine(), out age) || age < 0)
{
    Console.Write("Invalid. Enter a positive number: ");
}
Console.WriteLine($"Age: {age}");
```

### Sentinel-Controlled Loop

```csharp
string input = "";
while (input != "exit")
{
    Console.Write("Enter command: ");
    input = Console.ReadLine();
    Console.WriteLine($"You entered: {input}");
}
```

> **Key Point:** The while loop checks the condition BEFORE executing the block. If the condition is false initially, the block never executes. Ensure the loop variable changes to avoid infinite loops.

### do-while Alternative

The `do-while` loop guarantees at least one execution:

```csharp
do
{
    // Executes at least once
} while (condition);

